    "inscriptions": "The Lauderdale Lakes Country Club golf course owes it&apos;s existance to the tenacity of numerous area residents who stepped in to save it from development during its 100-plus year history. The course was created in 1921 to use by guests of the nearby Sterlingworth Hotel. In 1936, Lakes resident Edwin Hawks Ravenscroft bought and redesigned the course, which he had to shutter during World War II. At the end of the war, another resident, Waldemar Petersen, formed a group to buy the course from Ravenscroft and manage it. The group included: Chuck Morton, as secretary; Harold Leasley, as president; Petersen, as treasurer; and Phil May, Harold  Mattes, Harold schmid, Harold Pittman, Kirk shareholders. The group bought the course in December 1945, with Morton acting as volunteer manager. In 1973, after expanding the clubhouse, the group sold the course back to the Steringworth. Between 1973 and 1983, the course&apos;s zoning requirements were changed to allow multi-family condominium development, placing its continued existence in jeopardy. At this time a second group of concerned residents, led by Dennis Petersen (no relation). stepped in to save the property as a golf course. They kept i it off the development market until 1996. Waldemar Petersen&apos;s son, Jerry Petersen(as chairman of the newly formed Lauderdale Lakes Lake Management District), led the effort to buy the course and make it into a municipal course. The District acquired wetlands bordering the course along the shore of Mill Lake and placed the property in a conservation easement to ensure that it continues as open space. Thanks to all these far-sighted Lakes residents, the Lauderdale Lakes Country Club remains an enjoyable open space and Betty Avery, and Kenneth Holsman and Emily Morrison, as benefiting the whole community.",
